icobacter pylori infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastric biopsy histology","Rapid urease test","Serum antibody test","Stool antigen test","Urea breath test"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eurea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-invasive diagnostic test that detects active \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection. The test relies on the organism\u0027s urease enzyme activity, which breaks down radio-labeled urea into carbon dioxide that can be detected in breath samples.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid urease test\u003C/strong\u003E requires an invasive endoscopy to obtain gastric tissue. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum antibody test\u003C/strong\u003E cannot distinguish between current and past infections. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric biopsy histology\u003C/strong\u003E is invasive and would only be done as part of an endoscopy procedure. Whether or not this patient merited an endoscopy would depend on the severity of her symptoms and the presence of any red flags. The \u003Cstrong\u003Estool antigen test\u003C/strong\u003E, while non-invasive, is less convenient than the breath test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe urea breath test is preferred as the initial diagnostic test due to its high sensitivity and specificity, non-invasive nature, and ability to detect active infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Helicobacter pylori infection can be diagnosed through multiple non-invasive and invasive testing methods","The rapid urease test and urea breath test both rely on H. pylori\u0027s ability to produce urease enzyme","Diagnostic tests for H. pylori include serology, stool antigen, rapid urease test, urea breath test, and histology"],"references":["Azer SA, Awosika AO, Akhondi H. Gastritis. [Updated 2024 Jun 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: 